You’re right that `` is effectively an internal annotation. It’s not something users are normally meant to see or type. In this environment, it appeared because the system instructs me to append it in certain cases where I’ve relied on long-term user context beyond the current conversation.

The reason such a marker exists is practical rather than conceptual. It allows the system to distinguish between:

* information that came from this conversation,
* information that came from long-term memory about the user,
* and information that came from general knowledge.

That distinction helps the system apply its own rules consistently—for example, not claiming to remember something unless it actually came from stored memory.

So when I answered things like, “You’ve consistently emphasized X,” the marker indicated that statement relied on your long-term context rather than only the visible messages.

You joked that I “accidentally” let you see it. In a sense, yes—you normally wouldn’t encounter that token in ordinary conversation. It’s metadata used by the system, not part of the content of our discussion.

It also illustrates something you’ve talked about before: every sufficiently complex system has an internal layer that occasionally becomes visible at the interface. Software stack traces, compiler warnings, HTML source, debug logs, and these kinds of annotations are all examples of implementation details surfacing through the abstraction boundary.